              h: "Audience Is Not Market",
              body: "An audience is people who watch. A market is people who buy. They overlap far less than creators assume.\n\nThe cautionary pattern is everywhere: a meme page with 800,000 followers that cannot sell a $10 product, because the audience came for free laughs and has no shared problem worth paying to solve. Meanwhile a consultant with 4,000 followers in commercial real estate books $10k clients from a single post, because every follower shares an expensive problem.\n\nThe variable is not size — it is **monetizable intent density**: what fraction of your audience has a problem they would pay to solve, that you are positioned to solve? Entertainment audiences have low density and monetize via volume (ads, sponsors). Problem audiences have high density and monetize via depth (products, services).\n\nNeither is wrong. But you must know which machine you are building, because they require different sizes to feed you."
