              body: "Great copy is not written; it is rewritten — mostly by deletion. After the draft, run a cutting pass with these rules:\n\n- **Cut the throat-clearing.** The first sentence of most drafts is a warm-up. Delete it; the piece almost always improves. Often the real hook is hiding in sentence two or three.\n- **One idea per sentence.** Any sentence carrying two ideas becomes two sentences or loses one.\n- **Kill modifier flab.** 'Very', 'really', 'actually', 'just' — each deletion sharpens. Replace weak verb + adverb with one strong verb: 'ran quickly' is 'sprinted.'\n- **Concrete beats abstract.** 'Improve your engagement' becomes 'double your saves.'\n- **The 30% rule.** A strong target: the edit should shrink the draft by about a third with zero meaning lost.\n\nThen the read-aloud test — the oldest tool in the trade. Anywhere you stumble, the reader stalls. Anywhere you get bored, they are already gone. Fix exactly those spots and stop; over-editing past this point sands off the voice."
