              body: "Copy has a soundtrack even when read silently. All-short sentences feel breathless. All-long sentences suffocate. The craft is variation: a long sentence that builds a scene, unspooling clause by clause toward the point — then a short one. Like that. Gary Provost's famous riff on sentence-length music is worth pinning above your desk.\n\nDeploy rhythm tactically: short sentences at moments of decision ('Here's the offer.'), longer ones for storytelling and evidence. A one-line paragraph after a dense block lands like a spotlight.\n\nThen there is negative space — the visual layer of writing. On a phone screen, a wall of text is a skip signal before a single word is read. Break paragraphs every one to three sentences. Use line breaks as pacing devices in captions. Let key lines sit alone. Aim for roughly a 5th-to-7th-grade reading ease — not because readers are unintelligent, but because they are walking, half-watching TV, deciding in milliseconds whether you are worth effort. Friction anywhere is exit everywhere."
